	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Which is the Most Accurate NES Emulator?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Like I always say, running a large number of games is not a sign of accuracy. Commercial games (and newer homebrew games) are finished programs, which have been tested and bug fixed for release. This means that they are (usually) well behaved programs, that do most of their work according to the book, so a higher level simulation of the system is often enough to support them well. Things are very different during the development of a new game: you'll find yourself writing to wrong memory locations, extrapolating VBlank time, forgetting to initialize registers... and that's when accuracy is really needed, otherwise those problems might go undetected if the emulator is too forgiving with the little details.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


